-- ============================================================
-- Abstraction:  FlagSyncEN
-- Description:  Plain-English CLOOMC++ for DijkstraFlag synchronisation
-- Author:       Church Machine Educational Platform
-- Version:      1.0
-- Created:      2026-05-13
-- Language:     English
-- Dependencies: DijkstraFlag (NS slot 10)
-- ============================================================
-- Methods:
--   1. RunSequence() — exercise all four operations in order
--   2. Produce()     — V() operation: signal the flag
--   3. Consume()     — P() then Reset: wait, then clear the flag
--   4. Peek()        — non-blocking Test, flag unchanged
-- ============================================================
-- ENGLISH: FlagSync — DijkstraFlag Synchronisation Primitive
-- ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
--
-- DijkstraFlag is a one-bit synchronisation primitive that
-- implements Dijkstra's classic semaphore operations:
--
--   Signal — V(): raise the flag (wake one blocked waiter, or
--             set it for the next Wait caller to consume)
--   Wait   — P(): block until the flag is signaled; consumes
--             the signal immediately if already raised
--   Reset  — Lower the flag without consuming the signal;
--             use to clear a flag after inspecting it
--   Test   — Non-blocking read; returns 1 if signaled, 0 if not
--
-- FlagSyncEN is the same abstraction as the JavaScript FlagSync
-- and the Haskell FlagSyncHS, written in plain-English CLOOMC++.
-- Load all three front-ends side by side to see how the same
-- synchronisation logic looks in each notation.
--
-- Typical producer/consumer pattern:
--
--   producer:  call Produce  -- data is ready
--   consumer:  call Consume  -- blocks until data arrives, then clears
--
-- ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Create an abstraction called FlagSyncEN

It needs DijkstraFlag

-- Peek: non-blocking read of the flag state.
-- Returns 1 if the flag is currently signaled, 0 otherwise.
-- The flag is left unchanged — no signal is consumed.
Add a method called Peek

Set state to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Test

Return state

-- Produce: V() — signal the flag.
-- Raises the flag so the next Wait call returns immediately.
-- Returns 1 if a sleeping waiter was woken, 0 if the flag was simply set.
Add a method called Produce

Set result to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Signal

Return result

-- Consume: P() then Reset — wait until signaled, then clear.
-- Blocks the calling thread until the flag is raised.
-- Resets the flag so the next Consume call will also block.
-- Returns the Wait result (always 1 when the flag was signaled).
Add a method called Consume

Set waited to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Wait
Call DijkstraFlag.Reset

Return waited

-- RunSequence: exercise all four DijkstraFlag operations in order.
-- Mirrors the assembly dijkstra_flag example step for step:
--   Step 1: Test   -> 0  (flag unsignaled at boot)
--   Step 2: Signal       raise flag
--   Step 3: Test   -> 1  (flag now signaled)
--   Step 4: Wait   -> 1  (flag already up, returns immediately)
--   Step 5: Reset        lower flag
--   Step 6: Test   -> 0  (flag cleared)
-- Returns the final Test result (0 = cleared, 1 = still raised).
Add a method called RunSequence

Set before to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Test
Call DijkstraFlag.Signal
Set afterSignal to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Test
Set afterWait to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Wait
Call DijkstraFlag.Reset
Set afterReset to the result of calling DijkstraFlag.Test

Return afterReset
